        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Marie Rose sauce was invented in British restaurants in the 1960s. It became best known as the dressing for prawn cocktail, which appeared on nearly every British starter menu for two decades. On a jacket potato it feels nostalgic and slightly special. Cold and creamy against hot and salty is a reliable combination.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
